#. type: Content of: <section><title>
#: en/content/installation/upgrading-windows.xml:6
msgid "Upgrading Windows Installer"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><para>
#: en/content/installation/upgrading-windows.xml:8
msgid ""
"If you installed OTRS on Windows, it is possible to upgrade seamlessly by "
"downloading the new Windows Installer and running it.  The installer will "
"automatically detect the OTRS installation and perform an upgrade on it. The "
"installer will stop the OTRS services and start them after the installation "
"is complete, so your users will experience downtime. Make sure you plan some "
"time for the upgrade. Always make sure you have a backup of your server "
"before you start the upgrade procedure!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/upgrading-windows.xml:16
msgid "Performing patch level upgrades on Windows"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/upgrading-windows.xml:18
msgid ""
"If you need to install a 'patch level' upgrade (i.e. from OTRS 3.3.1 to OTRS "
"3.3.2) on Windows all you need to do is to download and run the new "
"installer. Of course you should make sure you have a backup in place before "
"you start the upgrade!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/upgrading-windows.xml:24
msgid "Performing minor level upgrades on Windows"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/upgrading-windows.xml:26
msgid ""
"Minor upgrades (from OTRS 3.2 to OTRS 3.3) take a little more time as there "
"is also a database upgrade step involved. The installer will detect this and "
"will automatically perform the upgrade for you.  After installation you "
"should still perform steps 12, 13 and 14 of the 'regular' <link linkend="
"\"upgrading\">upgrading section</link>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/upgrading-windows.xml:31
msgid ""
"Please note that if you have any additional packages such as Feature Add-Ons "
"installed on your OTRS system, you'll need to upgrade these as well. Make "
"sure you obtain these before you start the upgrade. After upgrade is "
"complete you can upgrade these packages via the Package Installer Web GUI.  "
"Packages from the 'standard' repositories such as Survey, FAQ and ITSM can "
"be upgraded from the Package Manager after the framework upgrade is complete."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><title>
#: en/content/installation/applications.xml:5
msgid "Additional applications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><abstract><para>
#: en/content/installation/applications.xml:9
msgid ""
"You can install additional application packages to extend the functionality "
"of the OTRS framework. This can be done via the package manager from the "
"Admin page, which downloads the applications from an online repository and "
"manages package dependencies. It is also possible to install packages from "
"local files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/applications.xml:15
msgid "FAQ"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/applications.xml:18
msgid ""
"The FAQ is the Knowledge Base component. It supports editing and viewing of "
"FAQ articles. Articles can be viewed and restricted to agents, customer "
"users, or anonymous users. These can also be structured into groups, and be "
"read in different languages."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:6
msgid "Installation from source (Linux, Unix)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:9
msgid "Preparing the installation from source"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:12
msgid ""
"If you want to install OTRS from source, first download the source archive "
"as .tar.gz, .tar.bz2, or .zip file from <ulink url=\"http://www.otrs.com/try/"
"\"> <citetitle>http://www.otrs.com/try/</citetitle> </ulink>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:19
msgid ""
"Unpack the archive (for example, using <command>tar</command>) into the "
"directory <filename>/opt</filename>, and rename the directory from otrs-x.x."
"x to otrs (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:24
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:/opt# tar xf /tmp/otrs-x.x.x.tar.gz\n"
"linux:/opt# mv otrs-x.x.x otrs\n"
"linux:/opt# ls\n"
"otrs\n"
"linux:/opt#\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:33
msgid "<emphasis>Script: First steps to install OTRS.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:37
msgid ""
"OTRS should NOT be run with root rights. Next you should add a new user for "
"OTRS. The home directory of this new user should be <filename>/opt/otrs</"
"filename>. If your web server is not running with the same user rights as "
"the new 'otrs' user, which is the case on most systems, you will need to add "
"the new 'otrs' user to the group of the web server user (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:43
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:/opt# useradd -r -d /opt/otrs/ -c 'OTRS user' otrs\n"
"linux:/opt# usermod -G nogroup otrs\n"
"linux:/opt#\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:50
msgid ""
"<emphasis>Script: Adding a new user 'otrs', and adding it to a group.</"
"emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:54
msgid ""
"Next, you have to copy some sample configuration files. The system will "
"later use the copied files. The files are located in <filename>/opt/otrs/"
"Kernel</filename> and <filename>/opt/otrs/Kernel/Config</filename> and have "
"the suffix .dist (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:59
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:/opt# cd otrs/Kernel/\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/Kernel# cp Config.pm.dist Config.pm\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/Kernel# cd Config\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/Kernel/Config# cp GenericAgent.pm.dist GenericAgent.pm\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:67
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Copying some sample files.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:71
msgid ""
"The last step to prepare the installation of OTRS is to set the proper "
"access rights for the files. You can use the script <command>otrs."
"SetPermissions.pl</command>, which is located in the <filename>bin</"
"filename> directory, in the home directory of the 'otrs' user. You can "
"execute the script with the following parameters:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><cmdsynopsis>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:77
msgid ""
"<command>otrs.SetPermissions.pl</command> <arg choice='req'> "
"<replaceable>Home directory of the OTRS user</replaceable> </arg> <arg "
"choice='req'> --otrs-user= <replaceable>OTRS user</replaceable> </arg> <arg "
"choice='req'> --web-user= <replaceable>Web server user</replaceable> </arg> "
"<arg choice='opt'> --otrs-group= <replaceable>Group of the OTRS user</"
"replaceable> </arg> <arg choice='opt'> --web-group= <replaceable>Group of "
"the web server user</replaceable> </arg>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:76
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:502
msgid "<placeholder type=\"cmdsynopsis\" id=\"0\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:101
msgid ""
"If your web server is running with the same user rights as user 'otrs', the "
"command to set the proper access rights is <command>otrs.SetPermissions.pl /"
"opt/otrs --otrs-user=otrs --web-user=otrs</command>. On SUSE systems the web "
"server is running with the user rights of 'wwwrun'. On Debian-based systems "
"this is 'www-data'. You would use the command <command>otrs.SetPermissions."
"pl /opt/otrs --otrs-user=otrs --web-user=wwwrun --otrs-group=nogroup --web-"
"group=www</command> to set the proper access rights."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:107
msgid "Installation of Perl modules"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:110
msgid ""
"OTRS requires some additional Perl modules, as described in Table 3-1. If "
"you install OTRS from source, you will need to install these modules "
"manually.  This can be done either with the package manager of your Linux "
"distribution (<application>yast</application>, <application>apt-get</"
"application>) or, as described in this section, through the Perl shell and "
"CPAN. If you're using ActiveState Perl, for instance on Windows, you could "
"use PPM, the built-in Perl Package Manager.  We recommend using your package "
"manager if possible."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:122
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:~# cd /opt/otrs/bin/\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/bin# ./otrs.CheckModules.pl\n"
"   o CGI..............................ok (v3.60)\n"
"   o Crypt::PasswdMD5.................ok (v1.3)\n"
"   o Crypt::SSLeay....................Not installed! (Optional - Required for Generic Interface SOAP SSL connections.)\n"
"   o CSS::Minifier....................ok (v0.01)\n"
"   o Date::Format.....................ok (v2.22)\n"
"   o Date::Pcalc......................ok (v1.2)\n"
"\n"
"   ...\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:117
msgid ""
"You can verify which modules you need to install with <command>otrs."
"CheckModules.pl</command>.  This script is located in the <filename>bin</"
"filename> directory, in the home directory of the 'otrs' user (see Script "
"below).  Please note that some modules are optional.  <placeholder type="
"\"screen\" id=\"0\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:137
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Checking needed modules.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:141
msgid ""
"You should strive to install the missing modules from your Linux "
"distribution's package management system. By doing so, the packages will be "
"automatically updated when new versions are available or when security "
"issues are found. Please refer to your distribution's documentation on how "
"to install additional packages. If the (correct version of) the module is "
"not available from the package repositories, you can also install from CPAN, "
"the Comprehensive Perl Archive Network."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:146
msgid ""
"To install one of the modules from above via CPAN, you have to execute the "
"command <command>perl -e shell -MCPAN</command>. The Perl shell will be "
"started in interactive mode and the CPAN module will be loaded. If CPAN is "
"already configured, you can install the modules with the command "
"<command>install</command> followed by the name of the module. CPAN takes "
"care of the dependencies of a module to other Perl modules and will let you "
"know if other modules are needed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:151
msgid ""
"Execute also the commands <command>perl -cw bin/cgi-bin/index.pl</command> "
"<command>perl -cw bin/cgi-bin/customer.pl</command> and <command>perl -cw "
"bin/otrs.PostMaster.pl</command> after changing into the directory "
"<filename>/opt/otrs</filename>.  If the output of both commands is \"syntax "
"OK\", your Perl is properly set up (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:161
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:~# cd /opt/otrs\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs# perl -cw bin/cgi-bin/index.pl\n"
"cgi-bin/installer.pl syntax OK\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs# perl -cw bin/cgi-bin/customer.pl\n"
"cgi-bin/customer.pl syntax OK\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs# perl -cw bin/otrs.PostMaster.pl\n"
"bin/otrs.PostMaster.pl syntax OK\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs#\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:172
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Syntax check.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:178
msgid "Configuring the Apache web server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:180
msgid ""
"First of all, you should install the Apache2 web server and mod_perl; you'd "
"typically do this from your systems package manager.  Below you'll find the "
"commands needed to set up Apache on the most popular Linux distributions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:187
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # rhel / centos:\n"
"    linux:# yum install httpd mod_perl\n"
"\n"
"    # suse:\n"
"    linux:# zypper install apache2-mod_perl\n"
"\n"
"    # debian/ubuntu:\n"
"    linux:# apt-get install apache2 libapache-mod-perl2\n"
"\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:200
msgid ""
"To access the web interface of OTRS via a short URL, Alias and ScriptAlias "
"entries are needed. Most <application>Apache</application> installations "
"have a <filename>conf.d</filename> directory included. On Linux systems you "
"can usually find this directory under <filename>/etc/apache</filename> or "
"<filename>/etc/apache2</filename>. Log in as root, change to the "
"<filename>conf.d</filename> directory and copy the appropriate template in "
"<filename>/opt/otrs/scripts/apache2-httpd.include.conf</filename> to a file "
"called <filename>otrs.conf</filename> in the Apache configuration directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:205
msgid ""
"Restart your web server to load the new configuration settings. On most "
"systems you can start/restart your web server with the command <command>/etc/"
"init.d/apache2 restart</command> (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:211
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:/etc/apache2/conf.d# /etc/init.d/apache2 restart\n"
"Forcing reload of web server: Apache2.\n"
"linux:/etc/apache2/conf.d#\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:218
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Restarting the web server.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:222
msgid "Now your web server should be configured for OTRS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:227
msgid "Configuring the database"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:230
msgid "Installing the OTRS database manually"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:233
msgid ""
"The recommended way to configure the database is to run the <link linkend="
"\"web-installer\">Web Installer</link>. If you can't use this for some "
"reason, you can also configure the database manually, as described in this "
"chapter.  If you can't use the web installer to setup the OTRS database, you "
"have to set it up manually. Scripts with the SQL statements to create and "
"configure the database are located in <filename>scripts/database</filename>, "
"in the home directory of the 'otrs' user (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para><screen>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:239
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:~# cd /opt/otrs/scripts/database/\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/scripts/database# ls\n"
"otrs-initial_insert.db2.sql         otrs-schema.mysql.sql\n"
"otrs-schema.oracle.sql\n"
"otrs-initial_insert.mssql.sql       otrs-schema-post.db2.sql\n"
"otrs-initial_insert.mysql.sql       otrs-schema.postgresql.sql\n"
"otrs-initial_insert.oracle.sql\n"
"otrs-initial_insert.postgresql.sql  otrs-schema-post.mssql.sql\n"
"otrs-initial_insert.xml             otrs-schema-post.mysql.sql\n"
"otrs-schema.db2.sql                 otrs-schema-post.oracle.sql\n"
" otrs-schema-post.postgresql.sql\n"
"otrs-schema.mssql.sql               otrs-schema.xml\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/scripts/database#\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:256
msgid ""
"<emphasis>Script: Files needed to create and configure the database.</"
"emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:260
msgid ""
"To setup the database for the different database back-ends, the .sql files "
"must be processed in a specific order."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para><orderedlist><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:265
msgid "Create the OTRS database manually step by step"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:268
msgid ""
"Creating the DB: Create the database that you want to use for OTRS, with "
"your database client or your database interface."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:273
msgid ""
"Creating the tables: With the otrs-schema.DatabaseType.sql files (e.g. "
"<filename>otrs-schema.oracle.sql</filename>, <filename>otrs-schema."
"postgresql.sql</filename>) you can create the tables in your OTRS database."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:279
msgid ""
"Inserting the initial system data: OTRS needs some initial system data to "
"work properly (e.g. the different ticket states, ticket and notification "
"types). Depending on the type of database that you are using, you will need "
"to use one of the following files: <filename>otrs-initial_insert.mysql.sql</"
"filename>, <filename>otrs-initial_insert.oracle.sql</filename>, "
"<filename>otrs-initial_insert.postgresql.sql</filename> or <filename>otrs-"
"initial_insert.mssql.sql </filename>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:288
msgid ""
"Creating references between tables: The last step is to create the "
"references between the different tables in the OTRS database. Use the otrs-"
"schema-post.DatabaseType.sql file to create these (e.g.  <filename>otrs-"
"schema-oracle.post.sql</filename>, <filename>otrs-schema-post.postgresql."
"sql</filename>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:296
msgid ""
"After you have finished the database setup, you should check and set proper "
"access rights for the OTRS database. It should be enough to grant access to "
"one user. Depending on the database server you are using, setting up the "
"access rights differs, but it should be possible either with your database "
"client or your graphical database front-end."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:301
msgid ""
"If your database and the access rights are configured properly, you have to "
"tell OTRS which database back-end you want to use and how the ticket system "
"can connect to the database. Open the file <filename>Kernel/Config.pm</"
"filename> located in the home directory of the 'otrs' user, and change the "
"parameters shown in the script below according to your needs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para><programlisting>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:307
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # DatabaseHost\n"
"    # (The database host.)\n"
"    $Self->{'DatabaseHost'} = 'localhost';\n"
"\n"
"    # Database\n"
"    # (The database name.)\n"
"    $Self->{Database} = 'otrs';\n"
"\n"
"    # DatabaseUser\n"
"    # (The database user.)\n"
"    $Self->{DatabaseUser} = 'otrs';\n"
"\n"
"    # DatabasePw\n"
"    # (The password of database user.)\n"
"    $Self->{DatabasePw} = 'some-pass';\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:327
msgid "<emphasis>Script: Parameters to be customized.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><title>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:335
msgid "Setting up the cron jobs for OTRS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:338
msgid ""
"OTRS needs some cron jobs to work properly. The cron jobs should be run with "
"the same user rights that were specified for the OTRS modules. That means "
"that the cron jobs must be inserted into the crontab file of the 'otrs' user."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <section><section><para>
#: en/content/installation/source.xml:342
msgid ""
"All scripts with the cron jobs are located in <filename>var/cron</filename>, "
"in the home directory of the 'otrs' user (see Script below)."
msgstr ""

